[5] Sierra Leone: How to support girls in post-Ebola Sierra Leone
Date: 17 Aug 2015
Source: World Economic Forum Agenda [edited]
https://agenda.weforum.org/2015/08/how-to-support-girls-in-post-ebola-sierra-leone/


While schools have re-opened in Sierra Leone, only a small number of students have actually come back to class. Some are working to support their families. Others are taking care of younger siblings. Some are deceased. But there is one population that is disproportionately missing: girls, especially pregnant girls. The Ministry of Education in Sierra Leone has banned girls who are "visibly" pregnant from taking the standardized exams that are needed to graduate, justifying this decision by saying pregnant girls "always fail" these exams. These girls are also not allowed to attend class, as officials believe it may have a negative influence on other girls. Even the First Lady of Sierra Leone, Sia Nyama Koroma, a well-known spokesperson for children's rights, also endorsed the pregnancy ban.

Yet, girls who get an education are more likely to escape poverty and live more productive lives. We know that educated women are more likely to ensure that their own children are educated. We also know that educated women are more likely to have fewer children. Given the poor economic state of Sierra Leone, it is an urgent priority to educate everyone, but girls and women are especially in need due to their increased risk factors and marginalization.

Sources:
*Girls education - the facts.
http://www.unesco.org/new/fileadmin/MULTIMEDIA/HQ/ED/GMR/images/2011/girls-factsheet-en.pdf
*BRAC commits to massive scale-up in girls' education
http://www.brac.net/node/1656#.VdJOGn3LLnl

[Byline; Yanoh Kay Jalloh]

