[6] Suspected, control, vaccine, research funding

17 Aug 2015 Italy: Suspected Ebola case in Turin
http://www.ansa.it/english/news/2015/08/17/suspected-ebola-case-in-turin_55e1417f-e545-4e14-af8e-a16e24fbefff.html
[A Gambian refugee was placed in isolation after going to the emergency room at Turin's Molinette Hospital with a very high fever and other symptoms possibly indicating he had Ebola virus disease (EVD). Hospital staff who came into contact with him took precautionary measures to prevent possible spread of the virus. The patient was transferred to isolation at Amedeo di Savoia Hospital, a facility with a specialty in treating infectious diseases.]

18 Aug 2015 Liberia: Ebola scares off trainee nurses in Liberia
http://allafrica.com/stories/201508181858.html
[Liberia lost nearly 200 health workers during the Ebola virus disease (EVD) outbreak, which killed more than 11 000 people across West Africa. The situation is getting more desperate as many considering a career in medicine are hesitating on moving forward until the EVD outbreak is over.]

17 Aug 2015 Sierra Leone: down to the last chain of Ebola virus transmission
http://goo.gl/QfccPU
[The country's use of rapid response teams and strong community efforts in finding Ebola virus disease (EVD) cases and contacts is showing results. An epidemiological week has now passed with no new EVD cases for the 1st time since the beginning of the outbreak. Now in phase 3, the EVD response is focusing on tracking each and every chain of Ebola virus transmission and closing down the remaining chains as quickly as possible. Sierra Leone is now down to a single chain of transmission. In addition to the index case, 2 more people (both of them from the young man's family) tested positive for EVD. They were treated at an Ebola Treatment Center which had been on standby and run by International Medical Corps (IMC). There, they were cared for by a team that included EVD survivors, who provided much of the physical and psychological care they needed. Both of the remaining cases are now recovering.]

16 Aug 2015 Sierra Leone: President Koroma warns against politicising Ebola
http://en.starafrica.com/news/sleones-koroma-warns-against-politicising-ebola.html
[He warns against cooking of Ebola numbers, a practice local officials have been accused of doing to make the picture of their effort against the disease look good if not impressive.]

19 Aug 2015 USA (New Jersey): Kennedy patient has malaria, not Ebola, officials say
http://www.nj.com/camden/index.ssf/2015/08/kennedy_patient_has_malaria_not_ebola_officials_sa.html
[According to Camden County Director of Nursing Claudia Funaro, the patient in a Stratford Hospital who possibly has the Ebola virus disease (EVD) has been confirmed by officials to have malaria, not EVD. The malaria was believed to have been acquired while the patient was traveling in West Africa...more]

19 Aug 2015 USA (New York): Patient with possible Ebola taken to NYC hospital
http://nypost.com/2015/08/19/patient-with-possible-ebola-taken-to-nyc-hospital/
[According to New York Fire Department officials (FDNY), on Wednesday (19 Aug 2015) a person who recently visited West Africa was rushed to Bellevue Hospital with Ebola-like symptoms, FDNY officials said. According to a spokesperson, the patient was suffering from symptoms associated with Ebola virus disease (EVD), including returning from recent travel in Guinea, and fit the FDNY's "criteria for fever travel." The patient was taken to the hospital by paramedics, and a command post had been set up at Bellevue hospital, with hazmat and decontamination units...more]

Control
------
18 Aug 2015: Quick, paper-based Ebola test may help in remote areas
http://consumer.healthday.com/infectious-disease-information-21/misc-infections-news-411/researchers-develop-paper-based-ebola-test-702115.html
[A paper-based testing device can quickly diagnose Ebola virus disease (EVD), yellow fever, or dengue fever. Once the blood sample is placed on the paper strip in the device, within minutes the paper changes to a specific color to indicate whether a person has Ebola virus disease (EVD), dengue fever or yellow fever. The test works in a similar manner to over-the-counter pregnancy tests. The components of the device will be given to people for free in free kits so they can build the device themselves. Their plan is to get the device into the field and to people who need it. While lab tests are more accurate, they require technical expertise, expensive equipment, transport to a lab facility, and often need refrigeration to keep the drawn blood specimen cooled. With this paper test device, people with EVD in remote areas can be quickly identified and placed in quarantine. The device was developed by researchers at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Harvard Medical School, and the U.S. Food and Drug Administration.]

[This has not been field tested yet, nor controlled against the gold standard PCR test for false positives and false negatives. - Mod.JW]

Vaccine
-----
15 Aug 2015 Guinea: plans Ebola inoculation campaign after vaccine success
http://www.lidtime.com/guinea-plans-ebola-inoculation-campaign-after-vaccine-success-6691
[Officials at the World Health Organization believe the effectiveness of the Ebola vaccine will end up being between 75 percent and 100 percent.]

19 Aug 2015 Russia: Ebola vaccine prepared for human trials
http://in.rbth.com/news/2015/08/19/rusian-ebola-vaccine-prepared-for-human-trials_391131
[Anna Popova, head of the consumer watchdog, Rospotrebnadzor, said on Wed [19 Aug 2015]: "The Ebola vaccine is undergoing registration and is being prepared for human clinical trials."]

Research
-----
17 Aug 2015 USA: Persistence of Ebola virus in sterilized wastewater
http://pubs.acs.org/doi/abs/10.1021/acs.estlett.5b00193
[We evaluated the persistence of Ebola virus spiked in sterilized domestic sewage... Infectious Ebola virus particles persisted for all 8 days of the test... While it remains unknown whether Ebola virus may be transmitted via wastewater, these data demonstrate a potential exposure route to infectious Ebola virus via wastewater and emphasize the value of a precautionary approach to wastewater handling in epidemic response.]

